\f0\fs12 \cf0 NOTES:\ * Memos reference beacons\ * index keyframes associate beacon vector to each slot\ * All keyframes associate beacon vector to the overall frame\ (consider compression schemes inside each keyframe?)\ * Beacons never get handed off, they're born, and they die\ * Beacons are selected by their longevity, consistency, and conformance to the target interval\ * All memo propagation can be vicarious via plumtree\ * keyframes are merged commutatively by comparing beacon vectors for each slot\ * each slab may be a beacon\ * beacons which are unpopular will tend to self-terminate\ * beacons which are popular will tend to persist\ * each slab's probability of activating its beacon function is inversely proportionate to the health of it's beacon set\ * does plum tree allow for popularity estimation?}

\f0\b\fs14 \cf2 Slab behaviors:\ \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural
\b0\fs12 \cf2 \'95 Store "memos" (in RAM or otherwise)\ \'95 Has specific storage/network/compute quotas (MB/GB/TB+)\ \'95 Track peering data with memo replicas (gossip, not all replicas)\ \'95 Report approx. expected lifetime (seconds~months+) to peers\ \'95 Calculate a "durability score" for all memos\ \'95 Push replicas of memos below durability-threshold to peers\ \'95 Send heartbeat packets to peer slabs\ \'95 Recalculate replication factor reduction for stale peers\ \'95 Accepts memo replicas from peers when below quotas\ \'95 Evicts LRU memos when network/storage quotas are exceeded\ \'95 Update peer slabs for memos leaving/entering\ \ \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural
\b\fs14 \cf2 Subjects/Memos \b0\fs12 \cf2 \ \'95 A subject is simply an enumeration, and exists only as a coalescence of it's projected memos \ \'95 Memos are immutable, originated by a slab\ \'95 The "HEAD" of a given subject consists of the most causally recent memos, which no other memos are yet known to descend.\ \ Notes:\ Term for memos that share the same topic which are non-identical\ Explain replica peering vs referential peering}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 \cocoascreenfonts1{\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset0 Helvetica;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural
\f0\fs16 \cf0 For an actor to commit a transaction, they must traverse each appropriate index for each edited record. ( primary index pictured )\ Upon locating the leaf node, issue a memo for the leaf referencing the updated values (if any) and the Memo ID(s) of the edit. If no values of the edit are pertinent to the index in question, the leaf memo shall be issued as a \i provisional \i0 memo.\ Then, issue a provisional memo for the parent index node (as non-leaf nodes do not specify full values), referencing the new child index memo, and repeat recursively all the way to the root node.\ Non-provisional memos are assimilated immediately by all peers receiving it. Provisional memos, in order to themselves be assimilated, must \i either \i0 be referenced by an active query context, \i or \i0 surpass a threshold based on the peering score, weighted by the inverse of the index tier. \ Very rough formula: A = (T/D) * P/10\ Contexts gather provisional memos until they are assimilated ( by whom? ) and a new (provisional) consolidated memo is generated. This has the effect of creating layers, which causes the causal linkage to become consolidated, and to gradually compact aging layers toward the base layer.}

\f2\fs14 \cf0 \ Expand B.1 -> \{ B.1, X.1, Y.1, Z.1 \} \f0\fs18 \
\f2\fs14 Expand Y.2 -> \{ - , X.3, Y.2, Z.3 \}\ \ We are able to easily determine, but do not care about:\ B1 \f3 \uc0\u8826 \f2 Y.2\ \ I only care to wait for B.2 because it's in the lineage of Y.2\ So how do I determine this?\ \ Do I need to fully expand Y.2 to search for B.1?\ What if my context was X.2?\ \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f2\fs14 Expand Y.2 -> \{ - , X.3, Y.2, Z.3 \}\ \ We are able to easily determine, but do not care about:\ B1 \f3 \uc0\u8826 \f2 Y.2\ \ \ I only care to wait for B.2 because it's in the lineage of Y.2\ So how do I determine this?\ \ Do I need to fully expand Y.2 to search for B.1?\ What if my context was X.2?\ \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1404\cocoasubrtf470 \cocoascreenfonts1{\fonttbl\f0\fswiss\fcharset0 Helvetica;} {\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;} \pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural
\f0\fs16 \cf0 Context: \{X1.B123\}\ Read R1\ Get R1.C1\ \ How do you efficiently determine that R1.C2 is needed?\ Easy... you simply look up the value of R1 using C5.B2\ How about after that? Do we simply grow our context perpetually to include all used index nodes? This is sub-optimal. Will likely want to compress this. If traffic wasn't an issue, you could simply propagate peering changes to the index root, and hang on to all index roots, but this is quite undesirable.\ \ Approach: Use multi-layered gradually-consolidating index to enforce causal fences.\ Base index layer = global. New participants provided with Base Layer Root node\ \ For an actor to commit a transaction, they must traverse the index, and issue an edit memo for the appropriate leaf node, and all its parent nodes up to and including the root node. Edit memos for leaf\ nodes are applied immediately upon receipt without condition. Non-leaf node memos are rejected until\ they achieve a minimum peering threshold \i or \i0 they are referenced by a foreign context. \ \ Index nodes exist in a multi-dimensional space until "Compaction" consolidates / ratifies them, and key framing creates an efficient representation. Compaction occurs as a probabilistic function based on estimated number of peers. C = P / T\ \ }
